        parsed_args={
            'prompt': 'In {{spacex_s1_main}}, retrieve any discussion of what periods each entity was actually part of SpaceX operations on a close-date basis versus recast basis. Look for disclosure about how many months xAI and X were included in the actual results versus retrospective restatement. Also look for any risk factors or discussion about the analytical challenges or limitations of the retrospective recast accounting for investors.'
        }
    ),
    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='# Analysis of Entity Inclusion Periods and Retrospective Recast Accounting\n\nBased on a thorough review of all the provided prospectus fragments, here is what can be determined and what appears absent:\n\n---\n\n## What the Fragments Reveal About Actual vs. Recast Inclusion\n\n### Close-Date Timeline\n\n| Entity | Close Date | Acquired By |\n|--------|-----------|-------------|\n| Twitter | October 2022 | Elon Musk (personally) |\n| X.AI Corp | March 2023 | Began operations |\n| X Holdings Corp. (incl. X.AI Corp.) | March 28, 2025 | xAI ("X Merger") |\n| xAI (incl. X) | February 2, 2026 | SpaceX ("xAI Merger") |\n\n### Critical Structural Point\n\nThe fragments reveal an **indirect acquisition chain**: SpaceX never directly acquired X. Instead:\n\n1. xAI acquired X on **March 28, 2025**\n2. SpaceX acquired xAI on **February 2, 2026**\n\nThis means **X entered SpaceX\'s consolidated group only on February 2, 2026** — the date xAI became a wholly-owned subsidiary. Despite the X Merger closing nearly eleven months earlier, X\'s results would have flowed through xAI\'s standalone financial statements, not SpaceX\'s, until the xAI Merger closed.\n\n### Actual Consolidated Periods\n\nBased on the financial statement dates referenced throughout the fragments:\n\n- **Audited consolidated balance sheet**: as of **December 31, 2025 and 2024** (from the index of financial statements)\n- **Interim consolidated balance sheet**: as of **March 31, 2026**\n- **Audited statements of operations**: years ended **December 31, 2025, 2024, and 2023**\n- **Interim statements**: three months ended **March 31, 2026 and 2025**\n\nThis creates a meaningful distinction:\n\n| Entity | First Day of Actual SpaceX Consolidation | Approximate Months of Actual Results (through 3/31/2026) |\n|--------|------------------------------------------|----------------------------------------------------------|\n| xAI | February 2, 2026 | ~2 months |\n| X (via xAI) | February 2, 2026 | ~2 months |\n\nYet all financial statements — including years ended December 31, 2023, 2024, and 2025 — are presented as if SpaceX had always consolidated xAI and X. This means:\n\n- **For the year ended December 31, 2023**: ~12 months of purely retrospective recast data; zero actual months of consolidation\n- **For the year ended December 31, 2024**: ~12 months of purely retrospective recast data; zero actual months of consolidation\n- **For the year ended December 31, 2025**: ~12 months of purely retrospective recast data; zero actual months of consolidation (the xAI Merger closed after year-end)\n- **For the three months ended March 31, 2026**: ~2 months actual consolidation (February 2 – March 31, 2026); ~1 month recast (January 1 – February 1, 2026)\n\n**In other words, by the time the prospectus was issued, approximately two months of actual combined operations existed across all historical periods presented.**\n\n---\n\n## What the Fragments Do NOT Contain\n\nDespite careful review, the following are **not present** in the provided excerpts:\n\n### 1. No Explicit Disclosure of Actual vs. Recast Month Counts\n\nThe fragments do not include a passage that says something like "xAI was included in our results for X months on an actual basis and Y months on a recast basis." The accounting treatment is described in technical terms (common control, retrospective combination, historical carrying amounts), but the practical informational implication — that investors are looking at financials that only recently became "real" in a consolidated sense — is left unstated.\n\n### 2. No Risk Factor Addressing Analytical Limitations of the Recast\n\nThe one risk factor excerpt provided discusses:\n- The early-stage nature of the AI segment\n- Integration, scaling, and execution risks\n- The AI segment being "recently formed" and "still being fully integrated and optimized"\n\nHowever, this is a **business integration risk factor**, not a **financial reporting or analytical risk factor**. The fragments do not contain a risk factor warning investors that:\n\n- The historical financial data is substantially a retrospective accounting construct rather than a record of actual consolidated operations\n- Comparability across periods may be impaired because the recast combines entities that operated independently with different cost structures, capital allocation strategies, and related-party dynamics\n- Historical revenue, expense, and profitability figures do not reflect what SpaceX shareholders actually experienced in those periods\n- The recast eliminates intercompany transactions between entities that were under common control but operated as separate companies, potentially obscuring the true economic relationships\n\n### 3. No Discussion of Intercompany Elimination Effects\n\nThe fragments state multiple times that "all historical related party transactions between the entities have been eliminated in consolidation," but there is no quantitative discussion of how significant these eliminations were, or what the financial statements would have looked like without them. For example, if xAI was paying X Holdings for data access, or if SpaceX was providing launch services to xAI at preferential rates, those transactions would have been eliminated — but the investor is given no sense of magnitude.\n\n### 4. No Sensitivity or Pro Forma Comparison\n\nThere is no presentation of what the financials would look like on a standalone basis (i.e., SpaceX without xAI and X) versus the combined recast basis, which would be the most analytically useful comparison for an investor trying to understand the relative contributions of each business.\n\n---\n\n## The Accounting Rationale Provided\n\nThe fragments repeatedly explain *why* retrospective recast treatment is required:\n\n> "The Mergers have been accounted for as reorganizations of entities under common control as Mr. Elon Musk had a controlling financial interest in the Company, xAI and X through his majority voting interest in each such entity during the periods presented."\n\nThis is technically correct under U.S. GAAP (ASC 805-50, Transactions Between Entities Under Common Control). When entities under common control are combined, the financial statements are recast as if the entities had always been combined, using historical carrying amounts. No goodwill is recognized, and intercompany transactions are eliminated.\n\nHowever, the fragments also reveal an **exception** to full retrospective recasting:\n\n- **xAI\'s Redeemable Convertible Preferred Stock** was NOT retrospectively recast into SpaceX Common Stock for periods prior to the xAI Merger. It was presented as outstanding preferred stock in historical periods and only converted as of February 2, 2026.\n- This is described as being because "the xAI Redeemable Convertible Preferred Stock was legally outstanding during all historical periods prior to the xAI Merger and represented a separate equity class of a legally distinct predecessor entity."\n\nThis creates an inconsistency in the presentation: common stock is recast (as if always converted), but preferred stock is not recast (presented in its historical legal form). While this is defensible legally and under GAAP, it means that the historical equity structure shown in the financial statements is a hybrid — partly recast, partly historical — which could confuse investors analyzing dilution, share counts, or earnings per share across periods.\n\n---\n\n## Summary of Findings\n\n| Question | Finding |\n|----------|---------|\n| Was a monthly breakdown of actual vs. recast inclusion provided? | **No** — not in the fragments |\n| Were risk factors about recast accounting limitations included? | **No** — the risk factor cited addresses business integration, not reporting limitations |\n| Did the fragments disclose standalone vs. combined financials? | **No** |\n| Did the fragments quantify intercompany eliminations? | **No** |\n| Was there any discussion of analytical comparability challenges? | **No** |\n\nThe fragments collectively present the retrospective recast as a technical accounting requirement without translating it into an investor-oriented disclosure about what the numbers actually represent in terms of the company\'s real operational history as a combined entity. An investor reading these sections would understand *that* the financials were recast and *why* (common control), but would lack the context to assess *how much* of the historical data reflects actual consolidated operations versus accounting convention.',
